snippet.textDisplay: I have found over several years and experience with cars that have been flooded out are written off for a reason.  No matter how much you dry them out and get the car running you can guarantee electrical components will let you down one after another. They might seem to be an excellent buy but they are not, that's why they've been written off. The electrical components alone can cost you more than the vehicle is worth.  Better to buy a good car in the first place it will be cheaper in the long run.

snippet.textDisplay: The water doesnt make the oil look like that. Water and oil DONT mix. Antifreeze readily mixes with water and will make your oil look milky. Might wan't to investigate further! I ran a LS motor with cracked cylinder heads for two and a half years. I only ran distilled water for coolant, no antifreeze cause I knew the heads were cracked and leaking coolant into the engine. The water evaporates very quickly at engine temp. Had to fill the reservoir every week for 2 and a half years.  My oil never looked milky like that at any oil changes I did.

snippet.textDisplay:
Had completely flooded Freelander 2.0 diesel, water levels were 1 meter above the roof and it was in the water for about 2 weeks.

It didn't cost to much to repair but it took me whole summer to get it done. Now, I have to say this car is really weird. Water in the engine and the belt bearings that are dead means water level was hood or more, but the enterior looks good and electronics work, so yeah, really weird. Maybe someone washed it and replaced electronics?

Anyway, the main issue is you will have problems over time, even though you fix it now parts will die off one by one. Water that got in is not clean water but has a bunch of sand in it and other stuff. pretty much every moving part will be compromised. I had steering rack gone, steering pump, diesel pump, literally every wheel bearing, every belt bearing etc. I'm not sure what is the deal with this car but be aware that every moving system that got this dirty water in will give you problems at some point.

snippet.textDisplay: Something else that needs to be checked on a flood car are the wheel bearings. A friend bought a restored flooded Ford and several months after he bought it, the front left wheel bearing failed. When it was checked, it still had water in it from the flood, so whoever salvaged the car, had not checked the wheel bearings for water and cleaned and re-greased them. Result - new front wheel bearings needed.
snippet.textOriginal: Something else that needs to be checked on a flood car are the wheel bearings. A friend bought a restored flooded Ford and several months after he bought it, the front left wheel bearing failed. When it was checked, it still had water in it from the flood, so whoever salvaged the car, had not checked the wheel bearings for water and cleaned and re-greased them. Result - new front wheel bearings needed.
